.Mock-Induced Test Damage
****
David Heinemeier Hansson coined the term https://dhh.dk/2014/test-induced-design-damage.html[Test Induced Design Damage] to refer to harm caused to systems in the name of testability.
In practice, your authors don't recognise this as much of a problem - we find that systems are usually improved by the decoupling required to test them well.
We _do_ often see tests ruined by mocks though, so much so that mocks have become a bit of a dirty word in our circles.
This despite the fact that these circles spawned the technique, and wrote the book (http://www.growing-object-oriented-software.com[Growing Object-Oriented Software, Guided by Tests]).

The problem seems to be that, as well as implementing interfaces, mock frameworks allow us to specify the expected invocations of their methods, and what should be returned in those cases.
But expected calls and their results don't make for a human-readable description of expectations, as we saw in `RecommendationsTests`.

As we hope to show, this isn't an insurmountable problem - we just need to add a semantic layer on top of the raw mock specifications.
In practice though, very few developers take this step, leading to cryptic tests which are blamed on the use of mocking.
****

==== Refactoring Expectations

Refactoring code to gain an understanding of what it does, and then using that knowledge to drive further refactoring, is a powerful technique.
Let's apply it here, starting with perhaps the most fundamental refactoring, removing duplication by introducing a function.

Our starting point is the setting of expectations on the mocks in the first test:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.0:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#expectations
[source,java]
----
mockery.checking(new Expectations() {{
    oneOf(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(paris);
    will(returnValue(List.of(
        eiffelTower,
        louvre
    )));

    oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
        paris,
        eiffelTower.getLocation()
    );
    will(returnValue(5000));
    oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
        paris,
        louvre.getLocation()
    );
    will(returnValue(1000));

    oneOf(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(alton);
    will(returnValue(List.of(
        flowerFarm,
        watercressLine
    )));

    oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
        alton,
        flowerFarm.getLocation()
    );
    will(returnValue(5300));
    oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
        alton,
        watercressLine.getLocation()
    );
    will(returnValue(320));
}});
----
// end-insert

We keep on seeing a repeated:

[source,java]
----
oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
    somewhere,
    destination.getLocation()
);
will(returnValue(someInt));
----

Something repeated four times (actually 10 times in all the tests) must have a meaning, so let's create a function to represent whatever that is.
We select the first of the repeats:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.0:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#excerpt
[source,java]
----
oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
    paris,
    eiffelTower.getLocation()
);
will(returnValue(5000));
----
// end-insert

Now we "Extract Method", using the name `somethingSomethingDistance` until we can figure out what it is.
IntelliJ is smart enough to work out that, if the `somethingSomethingDistance` had three parameters, it could use it in three other places.
So we accept it's kind offer to add them, and end up with:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.1:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#expectations
[source,java]
----
mockery.checking(new Expectations() {{
    oneOf(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(paris);
    will(returnValue(List.of(
        eiffelTower,
        louvre
    )));

    somethingSomethingDistance(paris, eiffelTower, 5000);
    somethingSomethingDistance(paris, louvre, 1000);

    oneOf(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(alton);
    will(returnValue(List.of(
        flowerFarm,
        watercressLine
    )));

    somethingSomethingDistance(alton, flowerFarm, 5300);
    somethingSomethingDistance(alton, watercressLine, 320);
}

    private void somethingSomethingDistance(
        Location paris,
        FeaturedDestination eiffelTower,
        int i
    ) {
        oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
            paris,
            eiffelTower.getLocation()
        );
        will(returnValue(i));
    }
});
----
// end-insert

This is complicated by the new method being hosted by the anonymous `Expectations` subclass passed to `mockery.checking`, and spoiled a bit by IntelliJ's choice of parameter names `paris`, `eiffelTower` and `i`.
The latter is easy to fix at least, we know what the parameters are from their use:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.2:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#excerpt
[source,java]
----
private void somethingSomethingDistance(
    Location location,
    FeaturedDestination destination,
    int distanceInMeters
) {
    oneOf(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
        location,
        destination.getLocation()
    );
    will(returnValue(distanceInMeters));
}
----
// end-insert

OK, so `somethingSomethingDistance` means that when we call the `distanceInMetersBetween` with two locations, it returns `distanceInMeters`.
What does this mean?

Ah, it's setting up a _given_.
When we invoke this method we are saying "Given the distance from `location` to `destination` is `distanceInMeters`".
Let's rename it to `givenADistanceFrom`.

While we're there: we don't actually care that there is only `oneOf` in these cases, so we'll change that to `allowing`; and we'll group all the givens together at the top of the expectations where people expect them:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.3:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#expectations
[source,java]
----
mockery.checking(new Expectations() {{
    givenADistanceFrom(paris, eiffelTower, 5000);
    givenADistanceFrom(paris, louvre, 1000);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, flowerFarm, 5300);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, watercressLine, 320);

    oneOf(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(paris);
    will(returnValue(List.of(
        eiffelTower,
        louvre
    )));

    oneOf(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(alton);
    will(returnValue(List.of(
        flowerFarm,
        watercressLine
    )));
}
    private void givenADistanceFrom(
        Location location,
        FeaturedDestination destination,
        int distanceInMeters
    ) {
        allowing(distanceCalculator).distanceInMetersBetween(
            location,
            destination.getLocation()
        );
        will(returnValue(distanceInMeters));
    }
});
----
// end-insert

Ooh, this is beginning to read like a test.

Now we can see that those `featuredDestinations` calls are `givenFeaturedDestinationsFor`, and repeat the previous refactor:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.4:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#expectations
[source,java]
----
mockery.checking(new Expectations() {{
    givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(paris,
        eiffelTower, louvre
    );
    givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(alton,
        flowerFarm, watercressLine
    );
    givenADistanceFrom(paris, eiffelTower, 5000);
    givenADistanceFrom(paris, louvre, 1000);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, flowerFarm, 5300);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, watercressLine, 320);

}

    private void givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(
        Location location,
        FeaturedDestination... destinations
    ) {
        allowing(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(location);
        will(returnValue(Arrays.asList(destinations)));
    }
            ...
});
----
// end-insert

Those givens are still irritatingly scoped to this particular `Expectations`, so we can't use them in the other tests.
What we can do, is give each given its own `Expectations` block, checked by the `mockery` test field.
For example:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.5:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#excerpt
[source,java]
----
private void givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(
    Location location,
    FeaturedDestination... destinations
) {
    mockery.checking(new Expectations() {{
        allowing(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(location);
        will(returnValue(Arrays.asList(destinations)));
    }});
}
----
// end-insert

This last refactor is a good example of an algebraic transform of code.
We can transform a list of expectations inside a single block, to a list of blocks, each with a single expectation.

We can't always do this, especially when the code depends on when it is run (see <<actions>>).
In this case, setting expectations is an action, because it sets state in the mockery, but this refactor doesn't change their order, and in any case, `allowing` expectations are (mostly) insensitve to the order that they are set.

Depending on the `mockery` field rather than the containing `Expectations` lets us move the givens to top level of the test class, and the invocations out of the mass `checking` block.
Our test is now:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.6:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#test1
[source,java]
----
@Test
public void returns_recommendations_for_multi_location() {
    givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(paris,
        eiffelTower, louvre
    );
    givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(alton,
        flowerFarm, watercressLine
    );
    givenADistanceFrom(paris, eiffelTower, 5000);
    givenADistanceFrom(paris, louvre, 1000);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, flowerFarm, 5300);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, watercressLine, 320);

    assertEquals(
        List.of(
            new FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(alton, watercressLine, 320),
            new FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(paris, louvre, 1000),
            new FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(paris, eiffelTower, 5000),
            new FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(alton, flowerFarm, 5300)
        ),
        recommendations.recommendationsFor(Set.of(paris, alton))
    );
}
----
// end-insert

Again, we can safely reorder the givens provided that there is no interaction between them.

Now that the givens are available to all tests, we can use them in place of the raw mock calls everywhere.
If you're a regex wizard, you could probably conjure a couple of replaces.
We could pretend that we found a nice refactoring to do it automatically, but the truth is that it was easier in this case to do a little hand editing backed by frequent test-running.
This gives, for example:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.6:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.java#test2
[source,java]
----
@Test
public void deduplicates_using_smallest_distance() {
    givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(alton,
        flowerFarm, watercressLine
    );
    givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(froyle,
        flowerFarm, watercressLine
    );
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, flowerFarm, 5300);
    givenADistanceFrom(alton, watercressLine, 320);
    givenADistanceFrom(froyle, flowerFarm, 0);
    givenADistanceFrom(froyle, watercressLine, 6300);

    assertEquals(
        List.of(
            new FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(froyle, flowerFarm, 0),
            new FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(alton, watercressLine, 320)
        ),
        recommendations.recommendationsFor(Set.of(alton, froyle))
    );
}
----
// end-insert

This is arguably how the previous authors should have left these tests.
We'd even bet that we could show these to our product owner, and she would be able to tell us whether recommendations is doing the right thing.
Mocks don't have to result in uncommunicative tests, but we do have to work to get there.

Now, where were we?
Oh yes, we were going to refactor from interfaces to functions.

==== Introduce Functions

Before we do, this is a Kotlin book, so let's convert at least something to Kotlin.
We choose `Recommendations`, because we're a bit bored of the tests for now, and it will be usdul to remind ourselves what it looks like.
The following is the result of following the refactorings presented in <<streams-to-sequences>> and , <<functions-to-extension-functions>>:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.7:src/main/java/travelator/recommendations/Recommendations.kt
[source,kotlin]
----
class Recommendations(
    private val featuredDestinations: FeaturedDestinations,
    private val distanceCalculator: DistanceCalculator
) {
    fun recommendationsFor(
        journey: Set<Location>
    ): List<FeaturedDestinationSuggestion> =
        journey
            .flatMap { location -> recommendationsFor(location) }
            .deduplicated()
            .sortedBy { it.distanceMeters }

    fun recommendationsFor(
        location: Location
    ): List<FeaturedDestinationSuggestion> =
        featuredDestinations.findCloseTo(location)
            .map { featuredDestination ->
                FeaturedDestinationSuggestion(
                    location,
                    featuredDestination,
                    distanceCalculator.distanceInMetersBetween(
                        location,
                        featuredDestination.location
                    )
                )
            }
}

private fun List<FeaturedDestinationSuggestion>.deduplicated() =
    groupBy { it.suggestion }
        .values
        .map { suggestionsWithSameDestination ->
            suggestionsWithSameDestination.closestToJourneyLocation()
        }

private fun List<FeaturedDestinationSuggestion>.closestToJourneyLocation() =
    minByOrNull { it.distanceMeters } ?: error("Unexpected empty group")
----
// end-insert

