==== Weaning Off Mocks

We're done with the production code now, but before we finish this chapter, let's return to the tests.
The tests used mocking because they had to implement a broad interface, even though most methods were not used.
We are still mocking, but now we are passing narrow interfaces (the function types) to the code under test, do we still need the mocks?

First of all, as a function type is actually an interface in Java and Kotlin, can we just mock that single-method interface rather than the whole of `FeaturedDestinations` and `DistanceCalculator`?

Before we can do that (zeroth of all?), we'll convert the tests to Kotlin, to avoid some of the issues that we'll otherwise have finding Java function types to express the operations.

The conversion is quite smooth.
We have to tell Kotlin to create a `@JVMField` for the JUnit extension before the tests will run,
and at the time of writing we had to reinstate the simple method references in the constructor call `(featuredDestinations::findCloseTo, distanceCalculator::distanceInMetersBetween)` because the converter created lambdas in their place.
This then is the setup:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.12:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#setup
[source,kotlin]
----
class RecommendationsTests {
    @JvmField
    @RegisterExtension
    var mockery: Mockery = JUnit5ClassMockery()
    private val distanceCalculator = mockery.mock(DistanceCalculator::class.java)
    private val featuredDestinations = mockery.mock(FeaturedDestinations::class.java)

    private val recommendations =
        Recommendations(
            featuredDestinations::findCloseTo,
            distanceCalculator::distanceInMetersBetween
        )
    ...
}
----
// end-insert

Where we create expectations on the mockery the syntax hardly plays to Kotlin's strengths, but the converted code works:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.12:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#givenFeaturedDestinationsFor
[source,kotlin]
----
private fun givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(
    location: Location,
    vararg destinations: FeaturedDestination
) {
    mockery.checking(object : Expectations() {
        init {
            allowing(featuredDestinations).findCloseTo(location)
            will(returnValue(destinations.toList()))
        }
    })
}
----
// end-insert

OK, what was first of all?
Oh yes, can we just mock the function types and not the fat interfaces?

It turns out that we can, but using raw JMock the getting the types right is hard.
https://github.com/dmcg/k-sera[k-sera] is a Kotlin wrapper around JMock that helps, so we'll add that to the build temporarily just to prove the point.
When we have, we can mock the function rather than the fat interfaces:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.13:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#setup
[source,kotlin]
----
class RecommendationsTests {
    @JvmField
    @RegisterExtension
    var mockery: Mockery = JUnit5ClassMockery()
    private val distanceInMetersBetween =
        mockery.mock<(Location, Location) -> Int>()
    private val featuredDestinations =
        mockery.mock<(Location) -> List<FeaturedDestination>>()

    private val recommendations =
        Recommendations(
            featuredDestinations,
            distanceInMetersBetween
        )

    ...
}
----
// end-insert

The method that we need to `expect` is now `invoke`:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.13:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#givenFeaturedDestinationsFor
[source,kotlin]
----
private fun givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(
    location: Location,
    vararg destinations: FeaturedDestination
) {
    mockery.expecting {
        allowing(featuredDestinations).invoke( // <1>
            location
        ).which will
            returnValue(destinations.toList())
    }
}
----
// end-insert

<1> `invoke` rather than `findCloseTo`.

This proves the point that we can mock function types, and set up expectations that they will be called.
We are now mocking only the 2 methods that we are actually invoking, which is better, but not as good as no mocking at all.

To remove the mocking altogether, we view a function type as a mapping between its input parameters as a tuple and its result.
So `destinationFinder` is a mapping between a single `Location` and a `List<FeaturedDestination>.
`distanceInMetersBetween` is a mapping between `Pair<Location, Location>` and `Int`.
We can express the desired result of this mapping as a `Map`.

Taking the `destinationFinder` case first, we'll create a property to hold the `Map` - `destinationLookup`:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.14:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#featuredDestinations
[source,kotlin]
----
private val featuredDestinations =
    mutableMapOf<Location, List<FeaturedDestination>>()
        .withDefault { emptyList() }
----
// end-insert

`givenFeaturedDestinationsFor` can populate the `destinationLookup` Map`:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.14:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#givenFeaturedDestinationsFor
[source,kotlin]
----
private fun givenFeaturedDestinationsFor(
    location: Location,
    vararg destinations: FeaturedDestination
) {
    featuredDestinations[location] = destinations.toList()
}
----
// end-insert

If we make `Recommendations` read out of `destinationLookup` we have passing tests:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.14:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#recommendations
[source,kotlin]
----
private val recommendations =
    Recommendations(
        featuredDestinations::getValue,
        distanceInMetersBetween
    )
----
// end-insert

`getValue` is an extension on `Map` that respects the defaults set up by the `Map.withDefault`, and hence does not return `null`.

Then it won't surprise you when we do the same for `distanceInMetersBetween`, removing all trace of the formal mocking:

