==== Have We Really Weaned Off Mocks Though?

Ah, now that is a good question!

In some ways we have just implemented a poor imitation of a mocking framework - we have no parameter matchers, no way of failing if a method isn't called, no way of expressing execution order.

Looked at another way though, we have implemented the recommendation engine's dependencies as two maps.
`Recommendations.recommendationsFor` is beginning to look like a simple calculation (<<calculations>>).
The result of that calculation depends on the `journey` parameter, and the contents of those maps that enable us to lookup featured destinations and distances.

As with our discussion around <<TOOD where is it>>, we know in reality that _when_ we call `recommendationsFor` does matter - it is really an action (<<actions>>).
Arguably the distance between locations won't change over time, but which destinations we find around a location will, as we add or remove them from whatever database they are held in.
Almost certainly though, the distinction is moot in this case, and we can treat `recommendationsFor` as a calculation.

At the beginning of this chapter, we viewed methods as functions with some of their arguments partially applied by capturing them as fields.
In tests we can reverse this process, making a function that takes all the inputs and testing that instead.
What does that look like?

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.18:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#recommendationsFor
[source,kotlin]
----
fun recommendationsFor(
    featuredDestinations: Map<Location, List<FeaturedDestination>>,
    distanceInMetersBetween: Map<Pair<Location, Location>, Int>,
    journey: Set<Location>
): List<FeaturedDestinationSuggestion> {
    val destinationsLookup = featuredDestinations.withDefault { emptyList() }
    val distanceLookup = distanceInMetersBetween.withDefault { -1 }
    val recommendations =
        Recommendations(
            destinationsLookup::getValue,
            distanceLookup::getValue
        )
    return recommendations.recommendationsFor(journey)
}
----
// end-insert

Here we create a new instance of `Recommendations` every call, so that it can capture immutable maps representing the rest of the data.
Note that this is a top-level function, there is no state in our tests at all.
Each test simply passes the data it needs to `recommendationsFor` - no need for setup or mutating the test fixture.
We can use a common lookup of distances, because they feel fixed, resulting in:

// begin-insert: tags/interfaces-to-functions.18:src/test/java/travelator/recommendations/RecommendationsTests.kt#excerpt
[source,kotlin]
----
class RecommendationsTests {
    companion object {
        val distanceInMetersBetween = mapOf(
            (paris to eiffelTower.location) to 5000,
            (paris to louvre.location) to 1000,
            (alton to flowerFarm.location) to 5300,
            (alton to watercressLine.location) to 320,
            (froyle to flowerFarm.location) to 0,
            (froyle to watercressLine.location) to 6300
        )
